
\subsection{Instantaneous heating} \label{analytical}
 The change in temperature felt at a given location r and time t due to the effect of a constant point source releasing q units of heat per second can there be written as \parencite{marcotte_importance_2010}:

\begin{equation}\label{CLHS}
    \Delta T (r,t) = \frac{q}{4 \pi \lambda t} erfc (\frac{r}{2 \sqrt{\alpha t}})
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}\label{CLHS}
    \Delta T (r,t) = \frac{Q}{4 \pi \alpha} E_1 \frac{r^2}{4 \alpha t} 
\end{equation}

 Q is the heat source strength per unit time ($m^2/\degree C.s$), $Q=q/\rho c$. In the case of a finite line source, the upper boundary is considered at constant undisturbed ground temperature T0. This is solved using a mirror image finite line source with similar load by opposite sign \parencite{zeng_finite_2002}. Using the infinite moving line source model, the time-dependent temperature variation in a 2D homogeneous medium caused by the heat source can be written as followed (\cite{jaeger1959conduction} in  \parencite{wagner_hydraulic_2014}): 

\begin{equation}\label{MLS}
\Delta T (x, y, t) = \frac{q}{\rho_m c_m (4 \pi \alpha) } exp(\frac{v_T x}{2 \alpha}) \int_0^{\frac{v_T^2 t}{4 \alpha t}} exp(- (\frac{x^2}{\alpha} + \frac{y^2}{\alpha})  \frac{v_T^2}{16 \alpha u} -u) \frac{du}{u}
\end{equation}

Memo

\[
T = \frac{T_0}{2} \frac{1}{\rho c (16 \pi \alpha)^(\frac{1+n}{2})} \exp{-\frac{x-v_T t}{\sqrt{4\alpha t}}} \times (erfc(-\frac{x-v_T t}{\sqrt{4\alpha t}})+\exp({\frac{xv_T}{2 \alpha}}) erfc(\frac{x+v_T t}{\sqrt{4\alpha t}}))
\]

\subsection{Fracture flow and heat transfers}

The Lauwerier-Pruess-Bodvarsson model \parencite{lauwerier_transport_1955, pruess1983thermal} set up a formula to predict the temperature of water $T_w$ in a fracture of aperture 2b at time t and distance x, where water injection commences at x= 0 and t =0.

\[
T_w - T_r = (T_i - T_r) erfc(\frac{c}{2b\rho_x c_w v_w}\sqrt{\frac{\lambda \rho c}{(t-\frac{xA\rho_w}{Q_w})}}) U(\theta-\epsilon)
\]
with $T_i$ the injected water temperature, $T_r$ the initial rock temperature, and $erfc$ the complementary error function. With flow velocity $v$ and injection flow rate $Q_w$, the equation can be rewritten for a generalized flow channel:

\[
T_w - T_r = (T_i - T_r) erfc(\frac{xP}{2 Q_w c_w}\sqrt{\frac{\lambda\rho c}{(t-\frac{x}{v_w})}}) U(\theta-\epsilon)
\]



In case of a heat flux boundary condition (Heat conduction - Neumann), the change in temperature on the surface $T_s$ and at a distance $z$, $T_z$ in the half space can be defined as follow (using $T \xrightarrow{}T_1 $ as  $ y \xrightarrow{ } \infty$):
\[
T_s = T_1 + \frac{2Q}{k}\sqrt{\frac{\alpha t}{\pi}}
\]
\[
T_z = T_1 + \frac{2Q}{\lambda} (\sqrt{\frac{\alpha t}{\pi}} \exp{(\frac{-z^2}{4 \alpha t})} - \frac{z}{2} erfc \frac{z}{ \sqrt{4 \alpha t}})
\]



This includes studies from i.e. \cite{angelotti_applicability_2018, brunetti_computationally_2017,  hecht2010evaluating, signorelli_sustainability_2005}.


Q = T0 * lambda_r # (W/m)
Q = T0 * lambda_m #Q = q / rho_c with q (W/m), lambda = alpha * rho_c, so q / lambda = T (Â°C) 





The solution for heat diffusion from a continuous heat source in a finite/infinite porous medium with a uniform initial temperature given in \cite{marcotte_importance_2010, molina-giraldo_heat_2011} is:

\begin{equation}\label{F_I_LS}
    \Delta T (r,t) =  \frac{q}{4 \pi \lambda r} erfc\frac{r}{\sqrt{4 \alpha t}}
\end{equation}

where erfc is the complementary error function.